    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nThe `virt_text_repeat_linebreak` option for `vim.api.nvim_buf_set_extmark` only applies to virtual text with `virt_text_pos = \"overlay\"` or `virt_text_win_col = <n>`. However, it doesn't apply to extmarks with `virt_text_pos = \"inline\"`.\n\nMy desired usecase is in neorg, where I add inline **virtual indentation** to lists for readability. 'breakindent' doesn't take into account the virtual indentation, which is expected, but then wrapped lines are no longer aligned to the orignal line. If I could add the virtual indentation to all wrapped lines via `virt_text_repeat_linebreak`, they would be aligned.\n\n## Example\n\nIf I have a raw file (no extmarks):\n```\n1|  original line with a two-space indent containing \n |  soft-wrapped text right here\n2|\n3|- list item with with \"n\" in 'formatoptions' and a\n |  'formatlistpat' that matches \"- \", with 'breakindent' on\n4|\n```\n\nIf my configuration adds four spaces as inline virtual text to the beginning of line 1 and 3,  this is the result regardless of whether `virt_text_repeat_linebreak` is true or false:\n```\n1|      original line with a two-space indent containing \n |  soft-wrapped text right here\n2|\n3|    - list item with with \"n\" in 'formatoptions' and a\n |  'formatlistpat' that matches \"- \", with 'breakindent' on\n4|\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe virtual text should be added to the original line as well as all wrapped lines if `virt_text_repeat_linebreak = true`, resulting in:\n```\n1|      original line with a two-space indent containing \n |      soft-wrapped text right here\n2|\n3|    - list item with with \"n\" in 'formatoptions' and a\n |      'formatlistpat' that matches \"- \", with 'breakindent' on\n4|\n```",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
